Cherokee Families,

We have had a student at Cherokee Middle School test positive for COVID-19. We have identified 21 students who were in close contact and will begin immediate quarantine. Every parent of a child who came into close contact has been personally notified. If you did not receive a phone call your child did not come into close contact with this individual. All of our quarantine procedures and contact tracing are guided by the State and County Health Department.

Thank you

post_text:
Good Morning,

We had a great start to our school year. We knew that as we move forward with onsite education we would learn to deal with COVID 19 on a daily basis. Today, we do not have any positive cases with our students but we do have students that have been exposed.

Students who are exposed are quarantined for the amount of time needed to be safe for return to school. In an effort to give you the autonomy to decide if your student should stay home, CPS is reporting that there are students in quarantine until August 31, 2020 for a 3 year old, 4 year old and 1st grade student. They have not tested positive but have been exposed. The school has been cleaned and we are taking social distance measures.

CPS will remain open at this time and will evaluate each situation individually. The situation changes almost hourly so further information will be provided as quickly as can be accomodated. If you have questions, please contact Donna Anderson at 580-596-3391.

At the August 10th, 2020 board meeting the issue of PPE and the wearing of masks was voted on for policy.

The vote was to wear masks or face coverings that are PPE and school approved according to the dress policy. The vote determined that if social distancing was possible the mask or face covering could be removed. Places such as the cafeteria, outside classroom, auditorium and classrooms with few students who can social distance can remove their mask. The instructor in each class can determine if social distancing is appropriate. Students in 5th grade will wear face coverings or masks while at the middle school or high school and use the methods of social distancing at the elementary.… More

The pageant will be streamed at www.cherokeechiefs.tv

Cherokee JH/HS is offering online enrollment through FamilyID. To enroll visit:
https://www.familyid.com/cherokee-public-schools. The link is also posted to the Enrollment tab on the school website at www.cherokee.k12.ok.us.

post_text:
Cherokee FCCLA Members Attend Virtual National Leadership Conference

RESTON, VA – Family, Career and Community Leaders of America (FCCLA) held its first-ever Virtual National Leadership Conference since the organization was founded in 1945. Instead of gathering in-person and rocking red blazers in the nation’s capital as planned, Cherokee FCCLA students logged on to an online platform on July 7-9, 2020 which blended virtual reality and gamification technology to transform FCCLA’s National Leadership Conference into a dynamic, “on-demand” virtual experience. This year’s historic Virtual NLC was filled with keynote speakers, breakout sessions, leadership trainings, EXPO, Competitive Events,… More

post_text:
Masonic Student and Teacher of Today Awards:

The Masonic Student and Teacher of Today awards have been around for sixty years, and this program was designed to be a support for public schools in conjunction with American Education Week. Each year one boy and one girl are selected who exemplify citizenship, leadership, and scholarship. Teachers are also chosen based on a commitment to the principles of loyalty, dedication, and helpfulness.

This year the Cherokee Corinthian Masonic Lodge #307 is proud to award the Student and Teacher of Today awards to:
Seniors: Kyla Colvin and Dakota Dooley
8th Graders: Hope Jordan and Xander Jackson
5th Graders: Jocelyn Davis and Jose Castro
Elementary Teacher: Ms. Candi Davis
JH & HS Teacher: Mr. Jason Paris

Certificates will be distributed to the recipients at a later date.

Due to the number of students we have had sign up for Driver’s Education, we will now be offering two Driver’s Education sessions. Participants will be divided by age.

The first Driver’s Education session for the Summer of 2020 will begin June 15th. Participants in the course must turn 15 before June 15th.

The second session will begin July 13th. Participants in the second session must turn 15 before July 13th.

The cost of the class is $250. Money can be brought to the first day of class.

Classes will be held Monday - Thursday from 8 a.m to 12 p.m. Driving times will be scheduled the first week of class. A sign up sheet is located in the office at the high school. Office hours are Monday - Thursday from 9 a.m. to 1 pm.

A roster for each session will be posted Monday.

If there are any questions please feel free to contact Tanner Bowman.
Cell: (580) 884-9690
Email: bowmant@cherokee.k12.ok.us

Cherokee Complex and Playground

CPS will open the Sports complex for walkers and the elementary playground from 6:00am to 9:00pm on June 15th. If regulations are changed or required by the CDC or State Department of education, opening these areas will be revisited. No other summer activities will be scheduled for the Sports Complex or gym for the summer. The track will be open for public walking but the fields and gym are still closed except for limited student and coach workouts allowed by the OSSAA. We hope this will help our community slowly resume normal activities and increase everyone's ability to exercise safely.

Cherokee Public School is excited to provide our 2020 graduates with a graduation ceremony at the Cherokee Complex Football Field. On June 5th, at 7:00 pm, our graduating class will take the field and walk across the stage to celebrate their accomplishments and successes.

CPS will be abiding by the CDC regulations that start June 1st by requiring social distancing during the ceremony. We have not limited the number of attendees but ask that you stay home if you have been sick or have had a fever in the previous 72 hours. This is an open air activity and all precautions have been taken to assure the safety of guests. CPS is not responsible if illness occurs while attending this event. As always, use your judgement on activities to attend.

post_text:
Oklahoma’s Promise: ALERT for 10th-Grade Parents with Recent Income Loss

If your student is or was in the 10th grade during the 2019-20 school year and you anticipate that your 2020 income may be under the $55,000 application limit for the Oklahoma’s Promise scholarship due to recent reductions in your income, you may submit an application based on your 2020 estimated income. The application must be submitted prior to the June 30, 2020 deadline at https://secure.okcollegestart.org/applications/Oklahoma_Promise/apply.html?application_id=3544. You will be required to provide a copy of your 2020 federal tax return when completed to verify that your 2020 income was under $55,000. The application will be held as pending until the tax documentation is received. Please send any questions to okpromise@osrhe.edu or Mrs Jordan.

post_text:
👩‍🎓🧑‍🎓👨‍🎓Cherokee Graduation 2020👩‍🎓🧑‍🎓👨‍🎓

The administration team met and selected May 29th at 7:00 as the date to celebrate the class of 2020 with a graduation ceremony at the Cherokee Football Field. We will open the entire facility and practice social distancing as needed. Our Seniors are important and it is a very exciting to come together and give them a great ceremony to celebrate this amazing time of their lives.

We will watch the virus situation and if the City of Cherokee places restrictions on gatherings due to increasing numbers through May, we will devise a plan to have graduation virtually.

We are excited to share this special occasion with Chief family and friends. It’s a great day to be a graduating Chief!

In Oklahoma, we have 719 confirmed cases of Covid 19 with 30 fatalities. In the next two weeks the numbers, especially in Oklahoma, are expected to grow. Now is the time to stay home and distance so we do not lose ground on our fight against this virus. If you are 65 or older or immune compromised, shelter at home. Travel less and listen to the Governor’s press conference at 3PM for further guidelines.

When we do get to the peak, it will be vital that we stay with our shelter plans to reduce the possibility of relapse.…

CPS COVIS19 UPDATE #12

Not a lot new today. I took some time to be silly with the grand girls today. They are sheltering at home with us.

There are three things Id like to make sure our community knows:

1. We are feeding children ages 0-18 through the Summer Seamless Program, no questions asked. Sign your children up weekly for a weeks worth of breakfast and lunch. www.cherokee.k12.ok.us or call the school and press #5.

2. We are sending out a survey to gage our student’s ability to communicate with us virtually. Look for it and send it back. It’s important that we are able to serve all students. https://forms.gle/rBNf8VR5VLRgeGHA9

3. The OSSAA has informed us that all their activities are cancelled, not postponed, for the remainder of the year. There are no summer activities allowed until restrictions from the CDC are removed or revised.

Have a great weekend. Try and enjoy the beautiful weather while keeping social distance and remember we are all in this together and it’s going to be alright!

CPS UPDATE COVID19 #9

My notes from my phone call just now with the SDE and a little of this and that.

I want to write this to our senior class. I’m so very sorry you are missing the final days with your friends. So many important events…

Despite the School facilities being closed at this time please know that the Cherokee elementary school basement will be available for use if necessary in the event of a tornado warning. Please use the west main doors for entry. If you and your family seek safety in our elementary basement due to inclement weather, please be respectful of others and their personal space. Additionally, if you are showing signs and/or symptoms of being sick, please wear a face-mask in an attempt to minimize your chances of exposing those around you.

With these small requests of protecting yourself and those around you, we are confident we can safely gather in our elementary basement during dangerous weather conditions.

post_text:
CPS COVID19 Update #3

The State board will meet today at 4PM to discuss closure. This is the agenda. A conference call will be made with all schools tomorrow at 2PM. I look to have a decision at 4PM today.

If there is closure, CPS will proceed with our education action plan and will have a path developed to provide breakfast and lunch as a grab and go over the extended Spring Break.

It is my hope that a black and white decision is made for unity within public schools. The decision to close has a huge impact on so many communities and the health of our State is too important to leave as school to school decisions.

The decisions made are preventative and an effort to decrease community spread. I appreciate all of the prayers, texts and words of encouragement. These decisions are changing hourly and your kindness gives me peace of mind in decisions that must be made.

CPS will provide information as it becomes available and is reliable.

Thank you,
Donna Anderson
Superintendent
Cherokee Public School.

CPS has changed the calendar for the 2019-2020 school year. March 27, 2020 & April 3, 2020 will be days out of school. The calendar was changed in an effort to give the school community additional time to allow flu season to pass with as little spread of infection as possible.

LOCAL STUDENTS THROW HAT IN RING FOR STATE FCCLA OFFICE

Madison Wheeler and Bridget Wilhite of Cherokee, Oklahoma are two of 47 contenders vying for a position on the 10-person 2020-2021 state officer team of the Oklahoma CareerTech Family, Career and Community Leaders of America student organization.

Family and Consumer Sciences Education, and its affiliated student organization FCCLA, are integral components in the CareerTech system. This national student organization helps young men and women become leaders and address important personal, family, work, and societal issues. More than 10,000 students on Oklahoma high school and technology center campuses are members of FCCLA.
